    "created_at": "2019-09-01T17:08:13Z",
    "updated_at": "2019-09-01T17:08:13Z",
    "author_association": "MEMBER",
    "body": "I have sealed all the tests for networks <= Constantinople into LegacyTests  folder. Those tests are no longer need to be refilled. Only to execute (using retesteth -t LegacyTests)\r\n\r\nA test must be refilled if the hash of a filler file is changed. That usually means that something in the postCondition section of the test has changed. New fork expectations added or some changes to the pre state. \r\n\r\nI would strictly not recommend to use any scripts to refill the tests as it is basically not needed for the clients that just want to check if they are passing the tests. To check if the client is passing the tests you could now use retesteth tool: https://github.com/ethereum/retesteth\r\n\r\nIf, however you create your own test, you would need to generate the test for your fork changes. For this automatition is not needed as you have to manually set the post condition and verify that your test (precondition -> transaction -> postCondition check) is passing everything correctly. read retesteth docs on how to write your own state test: https://github.com/ethereum/retesteth/wiki/Creating-a-State-Test-with-retesteth\r\n\r\n",
